350","1335–1381":"1335–1381","1270–1320":"1270–1320","–Female":"Deceased","before 1335":"before 1335","before 1300":"before 1300","1350":"1350","1372":"1372","1381":"1381","1270":"1270","Abt 1372":"about 1372","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","Abt 1300":"about 1300","1300":"1300","Abt 1320":"about 1320","1320":"1320","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Abbey, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Abbey, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Innes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   McInnis  , from Gaelic <b>Mag Aonghuis</b> ‘son of Aonghus’.","Scottish: habitational name from the barony of Innes in Urquhart (Morayshire), named from Gaelic <i>inis</i> ‘island’.","English: variant of   Ince  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Inniss","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  ."]},{"name":"Ince","meanings":["habitational name from Ince in Makerfield (Lancashire), Ince (Cheshire), or Ince Blundell (Lancashire). The placenames derive from Proto-Welsh <i>ïnïs</i> ‘island’.","possibly a post-medieval West Midlands variant of <b>Hints</b>, a habitational name from either of two places called Hints (Staffordshire, Shropshire). The placenames probably derive from Proto-Welsh <i>hïnt</i> ‘way, path’ + Middle English plural <i>-es</i>.","possibly a variant with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i> of <i>Inn</i>, from residence at an <i>inn</i> or <i>inns</i>, from Middle English <i>in</i> (singular) or <i>innes</i> (plural) ‘tavern, lodging(s), tenement(s)’. There seems also to have been some confusion with Scottish   Innes  ."]},{"name":"Inch","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  .","English: perhaps, at least in some cases, a variant of   Ince  .","English: variant of   Hinch  ."]},{"name":"McInnis","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Aonghuis</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Aonghus</i> (see   Angus  ). See also   McInnes  , compare Irish   McGinnis  ."]},{"name":"Innis","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  .","English: variant of   Ince  ."]},{"name":"Inness","meanings":["Scottish (Durham and Northumberland): variant of   Innes  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Innes 7th of Innes - of that Ilk was born about 1300, in Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Sir William de Innes 6th of Innes - of that Ilk and Lady William de Innes, VI. He married Margaret Leslie before 1335. They were the parent